@DlORAMA And the “-o/a” endings aren’t inclusive to people who don’t identify with being male or female. So if your waiter was non-binary or unknown gender, instead of saying” mesero” or “mesera” you’d say “mesere”.

@DlORAMA No not really, it centers men and masculinity. Latinx isnt that easy to say in spanish, but people have been using the ending of “-e” to be gender neutral. Latine instead of latinx, since its easier to pronounce & follows conventions.
